    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a great start. I can definitely see my students getting excited about the civil rights aspect. However, some of the more conservative students or even a skeptical parent might ask why we don't just stick to \"procedural due process\"—you know, just making sure the government follows the rules and the steps correctly. How should I explain the difference to them so they understand why substantive due process is necessary?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Procedural due process only guarantees fair *methods*—like a proper hearing—but it doesn't judge the *content* of the law itself. Substantive due process steps in to prevent the government from passing fundamentally unjust laws, regardless of how carefully they are enacted. Think of it this way: you can follow all the correct rules, but if the rule itself is tyrannical, substantive due process says that rule is unconstitutional. Therefore, it is necessary to prevent the state from simply following its own rules to oppress its citizens.",
      "source": "target",
