    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That makes sense. But I wonder if some might argue that \"substantive due process\" is actually a bit dangerous because it gives judges too much power to decide what is \"just\" or \"unjust\" based on their own views rather than just following the text of the law. How would you address that critique in class?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "This critique highlights the central tension surrounding the doctrine, suggesting it allows judges to become \"super-legislators.\" Critics argue it invites judicial activism by allowing judges to impose their personal moral views onto the law. However, proponents argue that a Constitution is not merely a set of rules, but a framework protecting inherent human dignity. The counter-argument is that if fundamental rights are not protected against majority whims, they are not truly \"rights\" at all.",
      "source": "target",
